Comment: Biazzare and baffling artistic decision to remake this movie as a realistic looking CGI 'real life' movie. What's the point? The characters can't even emote as well as they do in 2D without looking uncanny. The original is a visual masterpiece, much more stunning and stylistically interesting to look at. Oh well I know the reason, remaking their classic 2D features as 'real life' movies is a lucrative business, but it honestly taints the artistic integrity of the Disney brand as a whole imo. This is worse than the straight to dvd sequels they used to churn out. The remakes are not even attempts at making something new, just a transfer to another medium with padding added in and a slightly darker tone.

Title: The Lion King Official Teaser Trailer
Comment: Ok, so let me get this straight: You guys have remade Sleeping Beauty (sort of), Cinderella, Alice In Wonderland, The Jungle Book, and Beauty and the Beast in the much less vibrant and expressive medium of live action. You currently have three trailers running alongside each other for Aladdin, Dumbo, and Jungle Book, showing that these are made very quickly and are going to be coming out one after the other constantly. And you have Mulan and I believe Little Mermaid, perhaps more, in the works. Showing that this trend isn't going to die down. Not to mention you're adding pointless expansions to Star Wars that don't utilize the extended universe and don't add anything particularly new or important to the story. Sequels are coming out by the dozen, from Finding Dory, to Toy Story 4, to Wreck It Ralph 2, to Incredibles 2 (not saying they're bad films. Just pretty pointless), and original films are becoming more and more slim as you pool all of your resources into sparking a sense of nostalgia... And this isn't even a live action reboot. It's just a clunky, less expressive form of animation that's probably easier to make.

Title: The Lion King Official Teaser Trailer
Comment:
*The young generation is in for a treat. This will make Frozen look like trash. Just PLEASE do not ruin this childhood classic, with SJW edits! Please!!!* The original is so pure in every sense. There is so much cultural significance in it, and it encapsulates so much.

Growing up. High hopes. The struggle for identity during young adult years. First love. Not giving up. Fighting for justice, Overcoming fears, Redemption, Making Ancestors Proud & Continuing the Circle of Life ect.

But overall I've got to say, my favourite is the European Pagan themes of Reincarnation, Rebirth via Reproduction, and Redemption run so deep. "He Lives in You", is an incredibly powerful song. Also, the way in which the European Writers so beautifully depict the spirit & nature of Africa, is phenomenal. There's a really deep respect there, and its art like this which inspires everyone, to have hope in an idea Greater, and to aim for something higher.

The original is, maybe not the most entertaining musical of all time, but EASILY the GOAT musical overall. 

"Circle of Life",
"We Are One",
"Just Cant Wait To Be King!",
"Be Prepared!",
"He Lives in You",
"Can You Feel The Love Tonight?"

*What other musical has this many ABSOLUTE CLASSICS?? Challengers welcome!!*

You can split this comment section in four: 

1. People who still don't get that animation is an industry, therefore every single product aims to make money. And that's not limited to remakes. 2. People acting like making money off nostalgia is a federal offense, not realising that their Simba plushie is a piece of nostalgia marketing.

3. People praising the teaser trailer without even being able to spell one sentence right and adding no thoughtful commentary whatsoever.

4. Grateful customers willing to experience the same movie in a new light, knowing they might not like it.

Title: The Lion King Official Teaser Trailer
Comment:
I'm incredibly iffy about this. On one hand, I'm willing to give it a chance. It's being directed by the same guy who did the live action jungle book remake, and that turned out really well. If the same care and attention is given here, it could be something well worth seeing and even be on par with the original.

On the other hand, I'm skeptical about some of the casting choices and the direction this might go. Doing things live action can take a lot away from what animation can do, so that worries me a bit.

Never the less, I am willing to give it a chance. Even if it turns out bad, we'll always have the original, and no one can take that from us.

Comment:
Ya know... * sigh * There was a time when Disney, and other movie makers, had the ability to make a film feel magical.
Alot of us adults, our parents, and lucky grandparents were able to experience this.

But, kids today will probably never understand. Yes, these will still be hailed by them as instant classics, surely.
But, no matter how many times Disney shits out another AAA grade movie/remake, they will never be able to capture that same euphoric feeling, or understand what made the movies so special.

I'm sad to say it...
but as we all get older, and fade away... the magic of cinema has gone too.

Title: The Lion King Official Teaser Trailer
Comment:
I genuinely want to be excited for this movie. The scenery and anything where the animals aren't acting human is gorgeous. But I fear this film will be too uncanny valley and preachy for me. 

I was in Kindergarten when the original came out and it was all my friends and I did- parties, make believe, getting us to eat grubs (I mean veggies). My love was so strong that when I had to write a parody in 6th grade, I wrote, "The Lyin' King," telling the story of the Bush's and Clinton's as elephants and donkeys during the Lewinsky scandal when Bush Jr. had to "go into hiding" and "reclaim the throne" as the people turned against Bill. (Honestly, to my surprise Bush won the election after Clinton, but I didn't understand enough about politics to care about it besides how it affected my parody. Ah, the ignorance of kids and my guilt ridden hindsight.) I hold the original so close to my heart that I literally can't wait to be disappointed by how you modernize and politicize a classic story, especially with such talent as Donald Glover and John Oliver (seriously? To my understanding Broderick didn't have an agenda behind voicing Simba, but I have to question your VA choices now. How you will justify Oliver's voice in an African-base film? Is Zazu no longer a hornbill, but instead a European Swallow as opposed to an African one [lol, Monty Python]... and why should this matter when they are voices?). I honestly look forward to seeing how you decide to make Timon and Pumbaa overtly gay (instead of a classic bromance that didn't have anything blatantly sexual in a cross-species mutually beneficial relationship, and instead of a classy "yeah we're gay, so what?" approach and then treating them like normal people), or making Shenzi, Bonsai and Ed some other form of non-hetero. I look forward to seeing how you will use Nala and the lionesses to "smash the patriarchy" despite the nature of lions, I look forward to your emasculation of Scar as a character (will he be gay too [would they have enough mojo to kill off a gay character? Or will Scar be exiled instead?] or simply have a cheapened back story and motivation), and I look forward to seeing how you will add poop jokes when Hakuna Matata is cringy enough with it's trombone-ified flatulence. 

tl;dr I look forward to seeing my childhood be called out for being in the 90s due to modern day politics and dilution of culture, and witnessing the destruction of a classic story due to preachy politics.

PS Why can't we have new stories instead of you guys rehashing old ones while preaching new messages? And if you feel the new stories are failing, maybe you need to look at the stories themselves instead of debasing yourselves by baiting the masses with nostalgia.The reason they are classics is because they have themes in common with multiple cultures in multiple time periods. Modernizing and politicizing only dates your work instead of making it timeless.

Comment:
Of course this movie is not going to replace the original movie. The original one was and still is a masterpiece. It was the second movie I saw on a movie theater and I can remember all the laughs and the crying I had that day. But to be honest I CANNOT WAIT to see this version, and it's not for the effects or the story, it's because it's going to give me access to a really nice period of my life, it's going to allow me to feel like a kid again, and I'm sure that I'm not going to have that if I just see the old version. For me, this is like living a second version of a really nice dream I had long time ago...
Everything else is just nagging...

I really don't know what do think about this....or Dumbo 2019, or Aladdin 2019 either for that matter.
I saw Disney's Aladdin three times in the cinema, and the same with The Lion King back in 1994, when I was 20 years old. I think maybe I was 7 or 8 the first time I saw Dumbo...
This seem like it would be targeted at those young enough to never having learned to appreciate 2D animation, and thus could never really get all that excited about any animated movie created before ca 1990.
Honestly, and this question goes out to whoever reads this and fits the bill, is anyone who saw and loved The Lion King back in 1994 at all interested in seeing this??

Title: The Lion King Official Teaser Trailer
Comment:
Eh... the magic is lost.  They're just animals now.  There's no style, no artistry.  The facial expressions won't work for actual animal faces.  You can't have the whimsical scenes of "Can't Wait to Be King", or for any of the other songs either.  

It worked ok for "Jungle Book", because the original story by Kipling was a more serious tale without whimsy... and as we saw, the most awkward scene in the new film was "I Want to Be Like You".  It felt very strange seeing an 'animal' behaving that way with its inflexible expression.  

Not to mention, with "The Lion King"... it was already near-perfection.  Change too much, omit those classic songs... what's left?  Changes will only damage it.

I was disgusted by the trailer but then I looked at the comments and I had to run to the toilet to upchuck my breakfast.

It's hideous how Disney believes they can make one of the most beautifully animated films of all time obsolete by vandalizing it with creepy CGi animals that they're passing off as live-action and superficially imitating the motions of the original film without understanding the nuances behind them. That washed-out, carelessly-composited shot at 0:03 imitating the opening shot of the real movie perfectly sums up just how much of a soulless cash-grab it is.

And, how can any of you morons in the comment section claim to be human beings with dignity? You are all degenerate livestock, shamelessly gorging yourselves on slushed-up table scraps.

Title: The Lion King Official Teaser Trailer
Comment: This is absolutely ridiculous. I never commented on youtube before, but this makes me angry. Lion King was one of those movies that made me fall in love with animation, and now I'm an animator myself. I find it sad that Hollywood would give millions of dollars to make the exact same movie shot by shot again, only in CG?! I am all for new tools in animation, I find it exciting to discover the new "brushes" of our time, but at least turn the angel of the camera for one second, or just rethink this a little more beyond the fact that now in 2018 we have the technology to make lion manes look real. I wonder about the pitch for this.. did it take the producers more than 5 seconds to present their "idea"? Just take a pen, and write an original script. I find this unnecessary,  boring, lazy and just insulting to those brilliant artists who made the original movie look beautiful with their amazing skills in animation, storyboarding and filmmaking in general. If the fact that the trailer has the exact same shots is a gag, and the movie will have a different angle to it, like the new Jungle Book had.. then pardon my french, and I will (maybe) go and watch it.
